# pytest-async-mock-isolation-patterns — History

## v1.2.0 (2026-06-07)

**Changed by:** Nuance audit pass 2 — restore guard-test recipes (nuance audit pass 2)
**Verification:** verified-ci (source PRs ProjectScylla #1210/#1310/#819/#1312/#1313)

### What changed

- Added new Detailed Steps subsection **"L — Guard / Precondition Test Recipes"** restoring the recipes lost when `mock-and-test-isolation-patterns` was superseded:
  - Parametrized multi-guard test — set ALL fields valid first, then null only the one under test (so the *intended* guard fires, not an earlier one)
  - `side_effect=[ok_result, fail_result]` for sequential `subprocess.run` guards
  - The `_is_setup` / `returncode` state-guard pattern (default `False` needs no mock; set `_is_setup = True` to reach later guards; concrete non-zero `returncode`)
  - Closure-guard-via-action-builder — invoke `actions[StateKey]()` directly without driving the state machine
  - Runner entry-point rule — add a runner-level test, don't only test the internal delegate
  - Local-import patch target for guard tests (defining module, not caller namespace)
- Added When-to-Use trigger (14): testing a RuntimeError/precondition guard where nulling one field trips an earlier guard, a closure guard is unreachable via the state machine, or a test calls the delegate instead of the runner entry point
- Added 7 Failed Attempts rows covering wrong-guard nulling, single-return subprocess mock, bare-MagicMock returncode, full-state-machine closure setup, delegate-only coverage, and caller-namespace patch target
- Added tags: `guard-tests`, `runtime-error`, `precondition-guard`, `parametrize`, `side-effect`, `closure-guard`, `action-builder`, `runner-entry-point`, `is-setup-state-guard`
- Added Verified On row: ProjectScylla PRs #1210/#1310/#819/#1312/#1313

### Why

The guard-test recipes were verbatim content in the superseded `mock-and-test-isolation-patterns` skill but were not carried into the v1.0.0 canonical merge — section K mentioned missing-assertion and local-import patterns but dropped the concrete RuntimeError/precondition guard recipes. A nuance audit flagged the loss. These recipes are the only documented way to make a *specific* sequential guard fire deterministically (parametrized all-valid-then-null, `side_effect` lists) and to test closures and runner entry points without fragile state-machine setup.

